title: Definitions for Angular JS 1.0.2
body:
Don't know if you're familiarized with Angular, but the reason I chose to split the modules in multiple files is because Angular itself does that. It does not come in one single file, and for a good reason: those modules, when loaded, either augment or modify the main Angular module (ng).

Having them in separate files, just like the Angular distribution itself, allows for the user to reference the definitions of the modules he/she is actually including and, thus, get the proper interfaces.

I'll be writing some tests next...

title: Updates to pass Tests/underscore-tests.ts
body:
Fixed bugs by using Tests/underscore-tests.ts

Note, there are still a few type errors with the test file directly, these are issues with typescript compiler as far as I can tell.  Adding correct type annotations to the test file results in the compiler type checking correctly.  Can see jbaldwin/underscore.d.ts/test.ts to see the modified lines.
### Detailed updates for underscore-types-1.4.ts:
- Removed header comments (unnecessary)
- Removed all Object function signatures, typescript does not coerce down
- to Object from a custom class implementation.  Just using any moving forward.
- Fixed issues chaining on OOP wrappers.
- Fixed issue with lastIndexOf(), the isSorted? bool was incorrect, changed to from? number.
- Added isEmpty() typing for arrays.
- Added clone() typing for arrays.
### Updates to README
- Fixed 404 error on links in README

title: Changed data type on "expires" option on jquery.cookie plugin.
body:
Hi,

After updating the definitions and switching the jquery.cookie plugin definition from my own one my code didn't compile anymore.
The expires option for jquery.cookie can be either a 'number' or a 'Date' object and it was only defined as type 'number' in the definition file ( https://github.com/carhartl/jquery-cookie#expires ).
Since there is no option to define 2 data types for a property it should be defined as 'any'.

title: Backbone Router now extends Events class in definition file.
body:
The Backbone.Router class did not previously extend Events in the
definition file. This caused the TypeScript compiler to raise an
error when calling one of the Events methods (such as on()) on an
instance of a router.

This change allows instances of classes derived from Backbone.Router
to call methods on the Events class that are inherited by the router.
